aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident in San Antonio, Texas
The accident occurred in San Antonio, Texas.
The accident occurred on August 9, 2014, at 07:34 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Bombardier CL600 2D24 - 900.
The defining event was a ground collision.
The flight was conducted under Part 121: Air carrier - Scheduled.
The accident number was CEN14LA430.
The aircraft registration was N943LR.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were 80 people involved in the accident with no injuries.
During pushback from the gate, the tug positioned the airplane on the taxiway.
Before disconnecting, the tug reversed and the airplane rolled forward while still attached to the tug.
As the airplane rolled past the tug, the tug impacted the left side of the fuselage.
The tow bar pin was found sheared.
It could not be determined if the pin failed before or during the tow operation.
The operator did not have an immediate means of communicating with the flight crew the need to apply the brakes while the tug was still attached.
The tug operator's postaccident urine test was positive for marijuana.
The positive marijuana test indicated prior use by the tug operator.
It could not be determined whether the tug operator was impaired by the effects of marijuana at the time of the event.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of this accident to be failure of the tow bar shear pin.
The failure of the tow bar shear pin resulted in the tug operator's loss of control of the airplane during pushback operations.
The tug operator's inability to communicate to the flight crew to apply the airplane's brakes contributed to the accident.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
San Antonio, Texas

## Date & Time: 
August 9, 2014, 07:34 Local

## Aircraft:
Bombardier CL600 2D24 - 900

## Defining Event:
Ground collision

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 121: Air carrier - Scheduled

## Accident Number:
CEN14LA430

## Registration:
N943LR

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
80 None

## Analysis

During pushback from the gate, the tug positioned the airplane on the taxiway. Before disconnecting, the tug reversed and the airplane rolled forward while still attached to the tug. As the airplane rolled past the tug, the tug impacted the left side of the fuselage. The tow bar pin was found sheared, but it could not be determined if the pin failed before or during the tow operation. Further, the operator did not have an immediate means of communicating with the flight crew the need to apply the brakes while the tug was still attached.

The tug operator's postaccident urine test was positive for marijuana, which indicated prior use. However, it could not be determined whether the tug operator was impaired by the effects of marijuana at the time of the event.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:

Failure of the tow bar shear pin, which resulted in the tug operator's loss of control of the airplane during pushback operations. Contributing to the accident was the tug operator's inability to communicate to the flight crew to apply the airplane's brakes.
